[code]@SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
public class SpecifiedHashMap<K, V> {

	public SpecifiedHashMap() {
		this(512);
	}

	public SpecifiedHashMap(int size) { // not actually the 'size'... higher this is, and lower hashes are, faster this becomes. ideally, this is greater than the largest hash
		entries = new Entry[size];
	}

	private Entry entries[];

	public void put(K key, V value) {
		int hash = key.hashCode() % entries.length;
		Entry entry = new Entry(key, value), old = entries[hash];
		if (old != null)
			entry.linked = old;
		entries[hash] = entry;
	}

	public V get(K key) {
		int hash = key.hashCode() % entries.length;
		Entry entry = entries[hash];
		while (entry != null) {
			if (key.equals(entry.key))
				return (V) entry.value;
			entry = entry.linked;
		}
		return null;
	}

	public void remove(K key) {
		int hash = key.hashCode() % entries.length;
		Entry entry = entries[hash], previous = entry;
		if (entry == null)
			return;
		if (entry.linked == null) {
			entries[hash] = null;
			return;
		}
		while (entry != null) {
			if (key.equals(entry.key)){
				previous.linked = entry;
				return;
			}
			previous = entry;
			entry = entry.linked;
		}
	}

	private class Entry<K, V> {

		public Entry(K key, V value) {
			this.key = key;
			this.value = value;
		}

		public K key;
		public V value;
		public Entry linked;

	}

}
[/code]

something i thought of today... with right conditions (that is, a good size value with preferably low and unique hashes, i.e. if you were to use the player class in a rsps as the key and override the hashcode to the player id and set the size to 2000, this would work optimally. yes, those are very specific conditions, not that it will dramatically decrease performance otherwise) will always be faster than a HashMap...

